[normal]Bedroom Tax[bold]Argument 1
[normal] -
[normal] 
[normal]It wil
[normal]l contain the housing benefit bill
[normal]This is a spurious argument as the saving is only achieved 
[normal]if the bedroom tax (penalty) is applied[bold]. If the tenant moves within the social rented sector to avoid the bedroom tax and the property is then occupied by a household that does not face a penalty 
[normal]no saving is achieved[bold]. Moreover if the tenant moves from the social rented sector to the private re
[normal]nted sector the 
[normal]housing benefit expenditure will rise[bold] as the local housing allowance for the (smaller) private rented sector property will be higher than the housing benefit on the social rented property. 
[normal]Equally important are the additional costs that ar
[normal]ise 
[normal]as a consequence.
[normal]There are other consequences includ
[normal]ing wasted expenditure where tenants are required to move from specially adapted accommodation. This can not only result in the new home needing adaptation it may also require the home from which they moved to be partially refurbished as the new tenant of 
[normal]that home does not need those adaptations.
[normal]The stress that is being reported will increase 
[normal]mental ill health and the consequences for people that rely on informal care will increase formal health and care expenditure.
[normal]Significant sums are being committed i
[normal]n the form of discretionary housing payments in an attempt to mitigate the worst effects of a bad policy.
[normal]Argument 2 - 
[normal]It makes better use of social housing
[normal]The extent to which the bedroom tax makes better use of the existing housing stock is questionable. Most local authorities and private registered 
[normal]providers 
[normal]already have schemes that are designed to address under occupation. 
[normal]There is a growing body of evid
[normal]ence that suggest the contrary. For example development and allocation strategies that are designed to support growing communities (such as those pioneered by 
[normal]Conservative 
[normal]Scottish Housing Minister Ian Lang
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]where property allocation strategies were design
[normal]ed to accommodate future growth in family size 
[normal]are likely to be practically impossible as a result of the ‘bedroom tax’. Imaginative policies that 
[normal]ensure that p
[normal]roperties that are difficult to 
[normal]let 
[normal]are contributing to housing people instead of standing empty
[normal] are likely to be undermined. 
[normal]A number of housing associations are 
[normal]already 
[normal]reporting 
[normal]difficulties in letting properties to people who would face a penalty under the bedroom tax
[normal], increasing the length of void rates.
[normal]Argument 3 - 
[normal]Many 
[normal]local authorities 
[normal]have 
[normal]people on waiting lists
[normal]The numbers on local authority housing waiting lists continue to grow
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]t is the supply of 
[normal]new lettings[bold] that is critical to meeting this need. Stock re-allocation between existing tenants does nothing to address the needs of people 
[normal]on the waiting list.
[normal]Conclusion[bold]27 September 2013
